Step 6 : PersonProcessor.class we need to create which will do the data process which is the second step after reader 
PersonProcessor.class
package com.codesnippet.SpringBatchDemo.config;

import com.codesnippet.SpringBatchDemo.entity.Person;
import org.springframework.batch.item.ItemProcessor;

public class PersonProcessor implements ItemProcessor<Person, Person> {

    // how we want to process the data we write here. So here we write the logic 
    // Defines how we want to process the data between reading and writing	
	@Override
	public Person process(Person person) throws Exception {

		 person.setFirstName(person.getFirstName().toUpperCase());
		 person.setLastName(person.getLastName().toUpperCase());

		return person;
	}
}

Step 6 : here we will configure our spring batch code here in this class 

SpringBatchConfig.class

package com.codesnippet.SpringBatchDemo.config;

import com.codesnippet.SpringBatchDemo.entity.Person;
import com.codesnippet.SpringBatchDemo.repository.PersonRepository;
import org.springframework.batch.core.Job;
import org.springframework.batch.core.Step;

import org.springframework.batch.core.configuration.annotation.EnableBatchProcessing;
import org.springframework.batch.core.job.builder.JobBuilder;
import org.springframework.batch.core.repository.JobRepository;
import org.springframework.batch.core.step.builder.StepBuilder;
import org.springframework.batch.item.data.RepositoryItemWriter;
import org.springframework.batch.item.file.FlatFileItemReader;
import org.springframework.batch.item.file.LineMapper;
import org.springframework.batch.item.file.builder.FlatFileItemReaderBuilder;
import org.springframework.batch.item.file.mapping.BeanWrapperFieldSetMapper;
import org.springframework.batch.item.file.mapping.DefaultLineMapper;
import org.springframework.batch.item.file.transform.DelimitedLineTokenizer;
import org.springframework.beans.factory.annotation.Autowired;
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Bean;
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Configuration;
import org.springframework.core.io.ClassPathResource;

import org.springframework.transaction.PlatformTransactionManager;

@EnableBatchProcessing // dont need to use this annotation because in new verson of spring batch its not needed because 
                       // spring boot auto configuaration handel this automatically 
@Configuration
public class SpringBatchConfig {

	@Autowired
	private PersonRepository personRepository;


    // Step 3: Reads data from the CSV file (people-1000.csv) and maps each line to a Person object
	@Bean
	public FlatFileItemReader<Person> reader() {
		return new FlatFileItemReaderBuilder<Person>()
				.name("personItemReader")
				.resource(new ClassPathResource("people-1000.csv"))
				.linesToSkip(1)// We write this because the first line of the CSV file contains column names (header)
				               //ex : name ,age, account_num etc
				.lineMapper(lineMapper())
				.targetType(Person.class)
				.build();
	}
	
	//Step 4: This code defines how each line in your CSV file is converted into a Person object — splitting the line by
	//commas and mapping the values to the matching fields in the Person class.
	private LineMapper<Person> lineMapper() {
		DefaultLineMapper<Person> lineMapper = new DefaultLineMapper<>();

		DelimitedLineTokenizer lineTokenizer = new DelimitedLineTokenizer();
		lineTokenizer.setDelimiter(",");
		lineTokenizer.setStrict(false);
		lineTokenizer.setNames("id", "userId", "firstName", "lastName", "gender", "email", "phone", "dateOfBirth", "jobTitle");

		BeanWrapperFieldSetMapper<Person> fieldSetMapper = new BeanWrapperFieldSetMapper<>();
		fieldSetMapper.setTargetType(Person.class);

		lineMapper.setLineTokenizer(lineTokenizer);
		lineMapper.setFieldSetMapper(fieldSetMapper);

		return lineMapper;
	}
    
	// Step 5: This method returns a new instance of PersonProcessor, which processes each Person item before writing
	// so here it calls the PersonProcessor class
	@Bean
	PersonProcessor processor() {
		return new PersonProcessor();
	}

    //Step 6 : This method defines a writer that saves each processed Person record into the database using the save()
	//method of PersonRepository. 
	@Bean
	RepositoryItemWriter<Person> writer() {
		RepositoryItemWriter<Person> writer = new RepositoryItemWriter<>();
		writer.setRepository(personRepository);// use the PersonRepository to save data
		writer.setMethodName("save");// call the save() method of the repository
		return writer;
	}



    //step 1 : we are creating a job from here. We call this from the controller class where we autowired this job in 
    //controller class. 	
	@Bean
	public Job job(JobRepository jobRepository, Step step) {
		return new JobBuilder("importPersons", jobRepository)
				.start(step)
				.build();
	}


    //Step 2 : here is the secong step in which we will create step in whci we have reader , process , writer   
	@Bean
	public Step step(JobRepository jobRepository, PlatformTransactionManager transactionManager) {
		return new StepBuilder("csv-import-step", jobRepository)
				.<Person, Person>chunk(10, transactionManager)//Processes data in chunks of 10 items at a time
                                                               //For example, if there are 1000 records, they will be
															   //processed in batches of 10.				
				.reader(reader())
				.processor(processor())
				.writer(writer())
				.build();
	}

}


By Running this it will add the 1000 records in the DB with Upper names (first name and last names)

✅ Exactly right!

When you **run this Spring Batch job**, here’s what happens step by step 👇

1. **Your REST API endpoint** `/jobs/importData` is called.
   → This triggers the Spring Batch **job** defined in your configuration.

2. **Reader** (`FlatFileItemReader`)
   → Reads data line by line from the file **`people-1000.csv`** (skipping the header).
   → Each line is mapped into a `Person` object.

3. **Processor** (`PersonProcessor`)
   → Takes each `Person` object and converts the
   `firstName` and `lastName` fields to **UPPERCASE**.

4. **Writer** (`RepositoryItemWriter`)
   → Saves each processed `Person` record into the **database** using `personRepository.save(person)`.

5. **Chunking (10)**
   → Records are processed in batches of 10 at a time until all 1000 are done.

---

✅ **So yes — after running the job:**

* All **1000 records** from the CSV file are inserted into your DB.
* Each record will have the **first name and last name stored in uppercase**.

